V3's `kerr_isco_joint_probe_5d.py` ran at a single spin a=0.9 for both branches. V4's audit ran the same fixture, **then extended to a spin sweep at 0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9, 0.99**. All 12 combinations produced the same stratum classification and null-tangent alignment 1.0000.

This is the **strongest version of the cross-fixture invariance claim**:

> *The lifted singularity's spectral signature is invariant not just across physically unrelated systems, but across the continuous one-parameter family of systems within Kerr (parameterized by spin a). The Bardeen-Press-Teukolsky family tangent in (r, E, x, a) physical space — which depends nontrivially on a — maps exactly onto the null direction of the lifted Hessian for every spin tested. The fact that |cos θ| = 1.0000 holds at every spin from a=0.1 (near-Schwarzschild) to a=0.99 (near-extremal) means the lift faithfully encodes the family geometry.*

Importantly: even as the prograde ISCO contracts toward r=M (the degenerate horizon at extremal Kerr), and as the retrograde ISCO grows monotonically away, the lift's structural invariants persist. **The lifted singularity is a structural object of the lifting construction, not an artifact of any specific spin choice or branch.**

This is what V3's Investigation 2 (extremal limit power-law) was probing more aggressively. The V4 audit confirms the structural invariants hold at a=0.99 but does NOT yet replicate V3's power-law scaling analysis of `r-r_h ~ (1-a)^(2/3)`. That would require an additional sweep with logarithmic spacing in (1-a) and power-law fits — out of scope for this initial reproduction.

